\subsection{Depth of Field}
\label{sec:dof}
(see
\href{https://www.largeformatphotography.info/articles/IntroToDoF.pdf}{DOF.pdf})

Given the set focus distance, near ($d_\mathrm{near}$) and far ($d_\mathrm{far}$) focus limits (being of
acceptable sharpness) can be calulated by
\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:near-far-focus}
  d_\mathrm{near/far}  = \frac{H \,
    d}{H \pm (d - f)}
\end{equation}
where $d$ is the focussing distance in mm.

<<nearfar85, echo = FALSE, fig.cap = 'Full format sensor',warning=FALSE,results='hide'>>=
full.nf.plot(85,1.2,max=100, log='xy')
@

For an 85\,mm lens the two distances are shown with respect to
focussing distance and aperture in \Fref{fig:nearfar85}. The
corresponding depth of field ($d_\mathrm{far} - d_\mathrm{near}$) is shown in \Fref{fig:dof85}.


<<dof85, echo = FALSE, fig.cap = 'Canon APC sensor',warning=FALSE,results='hide'>>=
